Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed that the Inventory Committee continue the physical count of all PPE items taking into consideration the prescribed procedural guidelines for inventory taking as provided in COA Circular No. 2020-06, to wit:
Use the inventory working papers provided by the General Service Office (GSO) as basis for inventory taking activities, taking into consideration the capitalization threshold of ₱15,000.00;
Record/document the daily physical count in a standard Inventory Count Form (ICF), which shall be used as the basis in the preparation of the RPCPPE after the physical count;
Tag all PPE items counted with new property stickers containing the information provided by the said Circular;
State clearly in the ICF the PPEs condition, found at station and not found during the physical count which described as “non-existing” or “missing,” as well as other relevant information of each PPE; and
Prepare the RPCPPE upon completion of the physical count.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive, concerned officials and employees agreed to:
Submit a justification on the above-listed deficiencies;
Design a well-planned procurement program that would eliminate the use of alternative methods in the procurement of catering services;
Ensure that Purchase Requests, Purchase Orders and Requests for Quotations for meals are duly supported with food specifications and payments for meals are based on the actual number of event attendees;
Submit Purchase Orders within the prescribed period, as well as the Acceptance and Inspection Reports of consumable and perishable items to this Office within 24 hours from acceptance of the items delivered.
Submit the necessary procurement documents pertaining to the payments for meals of returning residents undergoing quarantine from November 30, 2020 to November 22, 2021. Henceforth, procurement of catering services should be duly supported with the requisite documents.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive and concerned officials agreed to:
Prepare an Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern Plan and formulate policies and guidelines so that the necessity and propriety of hiring job order employees are justified;
Adopt the contract of service/MOA/job order between the LGU and the individual rather than notice of hiring for a more binding contract with the job hires;
Incorporate in the contract the services to be rendered and the number of man hours, and quantity and duration of the works to be performed by the job order personnel and require them to submit quantified accomplishment reports;
Discontinue hiring individuals prohibited under Section 4 of CSC Resolution No. 020790, and ensure that compensation of JOs are paid on a daily basis rather than monthly; and
In coordination with the department heads, assess and review the necessity of hiring job orders by considering the existence of regular employees who could perform some of the contracted work. Maximize the services of the regular employees and minimize the hiring of job orders.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

Adhere to the rules and regulations on accounting and reporting of donations per COA Circular No. 2020-009. Henceforth, instruct the MDRRMO to submit the required Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances together with the supporting documents such as the acknowledgement receipts for in-kind donations, official receipts for cash donations and inventory list of the undistributed items or goods;

Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to issue Official Receipts on all cash donations received and maintain a separate bank account with an authorized government depository bank; 

Delegate to the Acting General Services Officer the receiving of in-kind donations and the inventory and monitoring thereof; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to record in the books all in-kind donations and the cash donations under the Trust Liabilities-DRRMF account per Section B.4 of COA Circular No. 2014-002.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) adhere with the rules and regulations in the disbursement of funds pursuant to the above-cited rules and regulations and require the:

Admin. Officer IV/HRMO II/Acting Municipal Treasurer to submit the lacking supporting documents for payment of hazard pay as follows: Executive Order issued by LCE showing personnel were authorized to report for work during the period of implementation of Enhanced Community Quarantine (ECQ) and Daily Time Record indicating that concerned personnel reported during the specified period of ECQ per Section 4.3 and 4.5 of DBM Budget Circular No. 2020-1;

MDRRMO to submit the activity design and Memorandum of Agreement made by and between the Municipality and the Owners of private vehicles stating the responsibilities of both parties, the specific period within which the required services will be provided, the health protocols to be observed, provision that the gasoline will be used for COVID-19 related PPAs only, as well as, the summary of daily trips with the corresponding gasoline used during the period contrary to Section 3.1 to 3.4 of GPPB Circular No. 2020-01;

BAC Chairman to submit the procurement documents for purchase of gasoline required by Section 3.4 of GPPB Circular No. 2020-01 for  procurement on emergency cases; and

Municipal Accountant to submit the MunicipaI IATF Resolution as legal basis for granting cash incentives to Barangay Tanods during the period of ECQ, as well as certification of respective Punong Barangays that the Barangay Tanods reported for duty during the said period.

Henceforth, the concerned personnel see to it that all disbursements are duly supported with complete documentation to ensure the propriety, validity, and legality of transactions and to avoid suspension of disbursements in audit.
